            <h2><i class="fas fa-book-medical"></i> Understanding HCG Levels</h2>
            
            <h3><i class="fas fa-chart-line"></i> What is HCG?</h3>
            <p>Human Chorionic Gonadotropin (HCG) is a hormone produced during pregnancy. It's made by cells that form the placenta, which nourishes the egg after it has been fertilized and becomes attached to the uterine wall.</p>
            
            <h3><i class="fas fa-clock"></i> HCG Doubling Time</h3>
            <p>In early pregnancy, HCG levels typically double every 48-72 hours. This doubling time is an important indicator of a healthy pregnancy:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Normal doubling time:</strong> 48-72 hours in early pregnancy</li>
                <li><strong>Slower doubling:</strong> May indicate potential issues</li>
                <li><strong>Faster doubling:</strong> Usually normal, but could indicate multiple pregnancies</li>
                <li><strong>Declining levels:</strong> May indicate miscarriage or ectopic pregnancy</li>
            </ul>
            
